sentence: A good-enough GDP report and a barrage of earnings releases provides the backdrop for today's session, a day after the FOMC indicated its willingness to start raising rates next month provided economic data continue to remain favorable.
Looked at in isolation, the first look at Q2 GDP growth rate appears disappointing.
After all, the reported +2.3% growth pace came short of consensus expectations of +2.7% and 'whisper' numbers of +3% and higher.
But I am not disappointed as I am looking at this report in conjunction with the 'upgrade' to the Q1 growth pace (Q1 is no longer 'negative') and overall revisions to the last two years of GDP data.
All in all, this is an 'OK' report - not great, but not bad either.
Importantly, it is totally consistent with the Fed's assessment of the economy.
The FOMC sees the economy steadily improving and this report is in-line with that view.
The Fed left the door open for the first rate hike in their Wednesday statement, should economic data continue to provide a constructive view of the underlying economy.
We will see how the monthly non-farm payroll data brings up next week, but this report won't cause the Fed to delay a rate hike in September by itself.
Unlike the reassuringly improving picture of the U.S. economy, the picture emerging from the ongoing Q2 earnings season is anything but reassuring.
Growth is non-existent, companies are struggling to meet revenue estimates and guidance continues to be to the downside, causing estimates for the current period to keep coming down.

Including this morning's reports from Procter & Gamble ( PG ), Colgate Palmolive ( CL ) and others, we now have Q2 results from 324 S&P 500 members that combined account for 72.7% of the index's total market capitalization.
Total earnings for these 324 index members are up +1.6% on -1% lower revenues, with 69.8% beating EPS estimates and 46% coming ahead of top-line expectations.

As we have stated in this space repeatedly in recent days, these growth rates are materially below what we have been seeing from the same group of companies in other recent quarters, though the beat ratios compare favorably for earnings and remain on the low side for revenues.

The composite picture for Q2, combining the actual results from the 324 S&P 500 members that have reported results to estimates for the still-to-come 176 index members, is for total earnings to decline -1.7% from the same period last year on -4.4% lower revenues.

Estimates for the current period have been coming down as companies have been overwhelmingly guiding lower as they report Q2 results, in line with the well-established trend of the last couple of years.
Total earnings for the S&P 500 index are currently expected to be down -4.4% in Q3 from the same period last year, down from the roughly flat showing expected in early April.
